#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: containment-aware label placement (position + rotation + size, jointly).

Mike flagged Morocco as a case where the label could spill into the ocean or a
neighboring country - the previous pipeline picked the anchor point (pole of
inaccessibility) and the rotation (global min-bounding-rect angle) independently,
with neither one checked against whether the actual label would fit inside the
country at that position and angle.

This replaces that with a joint search per country: ~18 candidate interior points x
31 candidate angles (-90..90 in 6deg steps), measuring how far a line through each
point at each angle can extend before exiting the polygon (both the label-direction
span and the perpendicular clearance). Picks the (point, angle) that maximizes
available room, then caps each country's text size to what that room can actually
hold (calibrated against the existing area-based sizes), so a label is sized to its
real available space rather than just its country's area. Also damps rotation for
fragmented archipelago nations (Indonesia, Philippines) where the single largest
island isn't representative of the whole country's footprint, so a strong tilt from
one island doesn't get imposed on the whole label.

Net effect: Morocco rotates more decisively SW-NE (38 -> 48deg) at a safer interior
point; Vietnam tilts closer to true vertical (-52 -> -66deg); about half of all
countries (mostly small/compact ones - Kosovo, Qatar, Lesotho, etc.) get a smaller,
safer text size than the pure area-based formula was giving them.
Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_label_fit.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys, re

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

